<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-107-279 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 076 483</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  July 10 1991 n1561 p12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Dole beckons for East Germans. (East German electrical,electronics and metalworking employees face layoffs)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schneider, Karl.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Up to 50 percent of the 1.2 million workers in East Germanelectrical, electronics, and metalworking industries could be laidoff as the 10,000 state-owned businesses are transferred to theprivate sector.andP;  Over 101,000 electronics and electricalengineering workers will lose their jobs.andP;  Many workers are beingretained as part of the German social security system, but thisoption runs out at the end of 1991.andP;  The future for skilledworkers depends upon how quickly new enterprises replace thestate-run firms.andP;  The German government is offering financialincentives to entice companies, but there are difficulties inestablishing a business there that have limited new investment.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ElectronicsElectrical EngineeringEmploymentLayoffGermany, East.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>